# AR Mapping (Unity AR Foundation)

This repository contains a Unity project using **AR Foundation**, tested on **iPhone** with ARKit and Unity’s AR template. It is designed to demonstrate or serve as a starting point for building augmented reality features using Unity's cross-platform AR solution.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** This repository is intended for personal use, version control, and development tracking. It is **not a ready-made template or starter kit**. Files may require configuration depending on your platform, device, or Unity setup.

---

## 🧠 What Is AR Foundation?

[AR Foundation](https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.xr.arfoundation@latest) is a framework developed by Unity Technologies to allow cross-platform development of augmented reality experiences. It supports both ARKit (iOS) and ARCore (Android), letting you write once and deploy to both platforms (with some platform-specific configuration).

---

## 📱 Supported Platforms

- iOS (tested on iPhone 12 and up)
- Android (with ARCore support)
- Unity Editor (limited preview/testing via AR Simulator)

> ⚠️ iOS builds require Xcode and a valid Apple Developer profile to run on-device.

---

## 🧰 How to Get Started

### 🔧 Requirements

- **Unity Hub**
- **Unity 2020.3 LTS or newer** (this project was built on Unity `6000.1.4f1`)
- **AR Foundation** + **ARKit XR Plugin** (for iOS)
- **Xcode** (latest, for iOS builds)
- Git LFS (optional but recommended if you use large assets in future)

### 📦 Unity Packages Used

Make sure the following Unity packages are installed via **Package Manager**:

- `AR Foundation`
- `ARKit XR Plugin` (for iOS)
- `XR Interaction Toolkit` (if used)
- `Input System` (if used in code)

---

## 📁 Directory Overview

3D UI/
├── Assets/
│ ├── Scenes/
│ ├── Scripts/
│ ├── XR/
│ └── Resources/
├── Packages/
├── mobile/ <- Ignored. Contains platform libraries like libiPhone-lib.a
├── Temp/
├── Logs/
└── UserSettings/




---

## 🚫 .gitignore Highlights

We’ve excluded the following to reduce bloat and avoid committing platform-specific or system-generated files:

- `Library/` — Unity cache and metadata
- `Builds*/` — Platform-specific build folders
- `mobile/Libraries/libiPhone-lib.a` — iOS binary (over 100MB, ignored to prevent GitHub push errors)
- `*.xcworkspace` and `*.xcodeproj` — Generated by Unity/iOS builds
- `Temp/`, `Logs/`, `UserSettings/` — Local config and debug files

If your project fails to build due to missing packages or files, check the **Package Manager** inside Unity and re-import what’s missing.

